actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed FPS measurements and screenshots — they clearly isolate the problem.

This is a known limitation of SKCanvasView in Blazor: it uses Skia's CPU raster engine to draw into a byte buffer, which is then transferred to the HTML canvas via `putImageData`. Image resampling (scaling) is computationally expensive in this path, especially in WASM where CPU throughput is lower than native. SKGLView avoids this entirely by using WebGL for GPU-accelerated rendering.

Here's a workaround you can use while we investigate: pre-scale the image to your target dimensions once (outside the render loop), then draw the pre-scaled image at 1:1 in `OnPaintSurface`:

```csharp
// Cache as a field — dispose when target size changes or component disposes
private SKImage? _scaledImage;

private void UpdateScaledImage(SKImage originalImage, int targetWidth, int targetHeight)
{
    _scaledImage?.Dispose();
    using var surface = SKSurface.Create(new SKImageInfo(targetWidth, targetHeight));
    if (surface == null) return;
    surface.Canvas.DrawImage(originalImage, SKRect.Create(targetWidth, targetHeight));
    _scaledImage = surface.Snapshot();
}

// In OnPaintSurface, draw the cached image at 1:1 (no per-frame resampling):
if (_scaledImage != null)
    canvas.DrawImage(_scaledImage, SKRect.Create(targetWidth, targetHeight));
```

This moves the expensive resampling out of the per-frame render path. Call `UpdateScaledImage` once when the image loads or the target size changes. Remember to dispose `_scaledImage` when the component disposes.

You mentioned SKGLView has issues with DrawLine performance — would you be able to share more details on that? If we can resolve those issues, SKGLView would be the better choice for your use case since it handles scaling natively via GPU hardware.
